'''Philip Stanley Cassidy''' {{ post-nominals | country = HKG | CBE | JP }} (30 March 1889 – 14 May 1971) was a British and Hong Kong entrepreneur. He was ''taipan'' of the [[Hutchison Whampoa|John D. Hutchison & Co.]] and unofficial member of the [[Executive Council of Hong Kong|Executive Council]] and the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]].

==Biography==
Cassidy first came to Hong Kong in 1913 and worked for the [[Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corporation]] before he was invited into partnership of the [[Hutchison Whampoa|John D. Hutchison & Co.]], an import and export company, with his brother-in-law [[Thomas Ernest Pearce|T. E. Pearce]] in 1922. They set up a branch office in Canton in 1929 which ceased to operate in 1941.<ref>{{cite book|title=Hong Kong Business Symposium: A Compilation of Authoritative Views on the Administration, Commerce, and Resources of Britain's Far Eastern Outpost|first=José Maria|last=Braga|publisher=South China Morning Post, Limited|year=1957|page=450}}</ref> Cassidy became the ''taipan'' of the John D. Hutchison & Co. after Pearce was killed in the [[Battle of Hong Kong]] in 1941.<ref name="Richard"/> 

He was member of the [[Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce]] and was its chairman from 1948 to 1950 and again from 1951 to 1952. He was elected by the chamber of commerce to serve on the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]] in 1948 and served on the [[Executive Council of Hong Kong]] from 1951 to 1952.<ref name="HKGCC">{{cite book|title=Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce Report for the Year 1952|url=https://www.chamber.org.hk/FileUpload/201307181044477212/SKMBT_C45213071715450.pdf|author=Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce}}</ref>

He was also member of the Committee of the [[Diocesan Boy's School]] from 1922, director of the European [[Y.M.C.A.]], member of the Court of the [[University of Hong Kong]] from 1929, and officer of the [[St. John's Cathedral, Hong Kong|St. John's Cathedral]].<ref name="HKGCC"/> He was also a co-founder of Cheero Club established in 1935 to provide facilities for the entertainment and recreation of British forces in Hong Kong.

He announced his retirement from public service in 1952 and returned to London.<ref name="HKGCC"/> He became chairman of the [[Hong Kong House]] and was awarded [[Central Chancery of the Orders of Knighthood]] in 1959.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=1 January 1959|issue=41589|page=23|supp=y}}</ref>

Cassidy married Margaret Johnson Rodger, daughter of A. Rodger of the China Sugar Refinery on 15 January 1919 at the Union Church.<ref>{{cite newspaper|title=WEDDING AT THE UNION CHURCH|newspaper=Hong Kong Daily Press|page=2|date=16 January 1919}}</ref> They had a son named Richard Ross Forbes Cassidy, an architect in Scotland.<ref name="Richard">{{cite book|page=40|title=RIAS Quarterly|issue=16|year=2013|url=http://www.rias.org.uk/files/2014/224/A0C50C59-F139-7E51-C63F-D2D8E20F7C1D.pdf}}</ref>

